To round out the picture, here are the advanced concepts that explain how companies maintain their "lines" of business and protect their market position.
1. Business Ecosystems (The "Network" Strategy)
An ecosystem is a step beyond integration. Instead of owning every part of the chain (vertical) or buying every competitor (horizontal), a company creates a web of partners, developers, and services that all rely on each other.
The Concept: You don't need to own the supplier if you own the platform everyone is forced to use.
Example: Google’s Android. Google doesn’t make every Android phone (Samsung, Pixel, etc. do), but they control the ecosystem through the Play Store and Google Services.
2. Barriers to Entry (The "Moat")
When a company is successful vertically or horizontally, they build "moats" to stop others from doing the same.
Vertical Moat: Controlling a rare raw material so competitors can't even start production.
Horizontal Moat: Having so many users that it’s too hard for them to switch to a rival (called Switching Costs).
3. Core Competency (The "Engine")
This is the specific "DNA" or skill set that allows a company to expand.
The Logic: A company shouldn't just grow horizontally for the sake of it; they should only expand into areas where their Core Competency gives them an advantage.
Example: Honda’s core competency is making high-quality engines. This allowed them to move horizontally from motorcycles into cars, lawnmowers, and boat motors.
4. Value Chain Analysis
Developed by Michael Porter, this is a way to look at your business "vertically" to find where you actually make money. It breaks a company down into:
Primary Activities: Inbound logistics, operations, outbound logistics, marketing, and service.
Support Activities: Procurement, HR, and technology.
Goal: By analyzing these, a company decides whether to Verticalize (do it themselves) or Outsource (pay someone else).
5. Outsourcing vs. Insourcing (The "Vertical" Choice)
This is the daily decision-making version of vertical integration.
Insourcing: Bringing a process in-house to gain control (Vertical Integration).
Outsource (White Labeling): Paying another company to make the product, then putting your brand on it. This is a "horizontal" move to expand your product line without the "vertical" headache of manufacturing.
Quick Summary of Strategic "Whys"
Concept	The Question	The Goal
Ecosystem	Can we make everyone play in our yard?	Market dominance via influence.
Core Competency	What are we actually good at?	Smart, defensible expansion.
Value Chain	Where is the money being made?	Efficiency and cost-cutting.
Outsourcing	Should we just hire an expert?	Flexibility and staying "lean."
